I've experimented with a variation of this.<p>Something like ...<p><pre><code>  foreach($_REQUEST as $k=$v) {
    $REQUEST[$k] = mysql_real_escape_string($v);
  }

  $query = "INSERT INTO table VALUES('$REQUEST[email]', '$REQUEST[name]')";
</code></pre>
Problem is, this only works if you don't plan on modifying any of the values before you stick them in the database.<p>You could also do something like ...<p><pre><code>  $query = "INSERT INTO table VALUES('{$e('email')}', '{$e('email')}')";
  $e = 'esc';
  function esc($v) {
    mysql_real_escape_string($v);
  }
</code></pre>
But I think that looks pretty ugly.
